story_txt:
How it played out:


Aalto University had a space that was empty;


People from varying backgrounds filled said space;


Someone suggested taking 30 Aalto people to meet the 70,000 at Burning Man festival Nevada USA;


Nobody laughed at the idea;


Burning Man organisation loved the idea!;

We got a green light for an Art Installation;

Ideas were born, sparks flew and things got crazy;

Crazy turned to impossible, impossible turned into a project;
Filming of this insane journey began;

The folk lore legend: Väinämöinen (The original Gandalf) awoke from his slumber and requested an instrument worthy of him to play!


A Giant Pike Head Kantele (National Finnish Instrument) was born and we joined forces with Koistinen Kantele family (The Stradivarius of kantele's);


Our documentary permit was accepted by Burning Man;


We realised we had run out of funds and time;

Go go Indiegogo :-)

Lets start with our beautiful fish head art/instrument:We have built a prototype Pike head structure in Finland and will now have to recreate and rebuild this beast in Reno USA to be ready to ship to the desert.  This piece is our answer to the art application we successful made with Burning Man.  Now why a giant Pike head?Finland's national folk law which inspired the Lord of the rings 
mythology, speaks of a god by the name of Väinämöinen.  This bad ass 
wizard character fashioned a musical instrument from a giant Pike's jaw 
bone, the Kantele.  So to remember our storytelling roots and heritage 
we are bringing back the Pike with a modern twist.Currently all our funds have gone into the supplies, transportation and manufacturing of the Pike head.  The Pike head is made up of a precision cut plywood skeleton and a braided plywood veneer as its scales.  Our pike will be illuminated and contain solar technology to bring it to life.  Then finally the most unique part of the piece... the one of a kind hand crafted tongue instrument (Kantele).So now we should probably explain what we need this money for right :-)First off we have raised 6,000€ from Aalto University's Design Factory to get the project started, this was coupled with a lot of volunteers and endless nights. This project has been and continues to be a minefield of unknowns and unexpected  challenges.  We have to arrange transportation to and from multiple destinations with a few tonnes of material and supplies with each step of the way threatening to derail the whole project.  The costs so far for logistics and materials is just over 10,000€ However we were lucky to receive a grant of 7,500€ from TTER (Technical Student's support foundation), leaving us a current deficit of 2,500€Our Camp/Theme campKeeping the Kalevala (Finnish folk lore) theme we named our Finnish + friends, Camp: Tuonela, this means the Underworld.  At the camp we will have around 35 people sleeping and living, we must setup everything we need to survive in the desert for just over a week.  Including power, lighting, toilet facilities, cooking facilities and shade from the intense heat of the sun.Our camp will be another destination for our activities and interactions with the other desert dwellers know as Burners.  We are holding workshops, talks and musical performances there.  Aalto University's teachings and learning's can be present in the most unlikely of places :-)The camp creation, running and cleaning costs are currently at 8,000€Tickets, Travel, Accommodation and stuff to keep us aliveEach member of Aalto on Fire has personally invested an average of 3,000€, this is something we are not asking to be funded nor reimbursed as this project is one of commitment and dedication.  The Documentary!The most epic of journeys deserves to be shared to our student body but additionally to a wider audience.  We started filming on a budget of next to zero with the aim of editing a 10 - 20 min trailer type documentary for the likes of Youtube.  We successful had our application to film at Burning Man approved and then things got crazy big...YLE (Finland's national broadcast network) caught wind of our idea and suggested we join forces with Documentary film maker Oskari Pastila.  Oskari and recently joined our project and we are now going to film the entire journey in a feature length film aimed for distribution by YLE!!!!!!!!Oskari's previous work speaks for its self:http://www.knucklebonehead.comhttp://basketcase-film.com/http://www.taynnatarmoa.fihttps://vimeo.com/63230173This now gives us the ability to tell our story and hopefully inspire our students and all those out there that believe learning and development should be fun, adventurous, challenging and not without risk.Costs involved with the documentary, excluding post production are at 18,300€This leaves us with a current funding goal of 28,800€We have aimed at 25,001€ before some costs blew out however we hope we can exceed our goal and receive additional funding through grants.More updates to soon follow and we appreciate all the help and support!Some Perky pics:
